> Linked to #2878 to support this behaviour in the Java API.

Hi, do you mean that I can compute partial graph in Java? I have tried to use ONNXRuntime in Java. But I encounter a problem.

My onnx model has two output: _embedding_output_ and _last_hidden_state_, when I tried to only get  one output (e.g. _embedding_output_), I will hava a fatal error. My code is below:
```
Set<String> outputNames = new HashSet<>();
// only compute one output
outputNames.add("embedding_output");
Result res = session.run(inputs,outputNames);
```

issue.title: Partial graph execution made simple.

issue.body:
# **Overview:**
Implements partial graph execution feature to enable ORTModule coordination with PyTorch using a _single_ thread instead of _two_ threads as in the current master. Allows a sub-graph to be executed in a _PartialRun_ call which returns the state of the graph in addition to fetches. The state essentially holds on to intermediate tensors. Keeping the state around keeps things performant by avoiding exchanging intermediate tensors back and forth between subsequent partial graph run calls that can add significant overhead. It also simplifies the design.

Supersedes https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/7077 by keeping stuff stateless inside ONNX Runtime.

# **Block diagram:**

![partial_graph_execution-7](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1211949/116354311-147f4d00-a7ad-11eb-996b-e029388e94fc.png)


## **ORTModule:**
The python front-end for ONNX Runtime Training. It creates an ORT session that represents an ONNX graph to train on. Then using RunForward and RunBackward calls the training is conducted. A pair of RunForward and RunBackward calls is represented by a state called RunCtx, this state also contains PartialGraphExecutionState that captures the state of the graph after a partial graph run in ORT. Using this state the graph execution can be resumed. This state is essentially a list of intermediate tensors that are produced during a graph run. 

## **Training Agent:**
This acts as the proxy to C++ backend of ORT. It is a C++ layer that interacts with ORTModule using pybind. 

## **Inference Session:**
This is the entry point into ORT backend. It contains the PartialRun call that partially runs through a graph using a list of feeds and returns a list of fetches (if any). It invokes Partial Executor that either initializes or updates an existing Partial Graph Execution state with Execution Frame that contains list of intermediate tensors. 


# **Performance benefits:**
We are seeing **2.73% speed/throughput improvements** using partial graph execution change over master on zcode model.

In the below graph after running for 4.6K steps the throughput is as following:

1. Magenta line is PyTorch baseline: **3.197e+4**
2. Grey line is master from 04/15 with symbolic fix: **3.1979e+4**
3. Teal line is the same master commit from 04/15 + symbolic fix + partial graph execution change: **3.2863e+4**

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1211949/115932756-6a1cc800-a442-11eb-8939-1fb748c60dcd.png)

issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

There have been several related issues (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6790, https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3128) asking whether it is possible to only execute the relevant parts of the graph, when specific outputs are specified, rather than executing the whole graph and only returning the relevant output.

[This](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6790#issuecomment-784967212)  comment suggests that this functionality _is_ already implemented, just not exposed, so I wanted to confirm if that was the case, and whether there are plans to expose this, as the [current workaround](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6790#issuecomment-784967212) of exporting a separate subgraph is often not ideal.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using): 1.8

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Partial graph execution when a subset of outputs are requested

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
Exporting subgraphs as separate ONNX models
